data.content:
## Migration Guide: BackgroundProcessor to .NET 8

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | Works, but `CancellationToken` is idiomatic |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(ct);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, ct);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false AND Thread.Abort)
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait for graceful exit up to timeout
            using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout.Value);
            try
            {
                await _workerTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // Worker didn't stop in time — log and move on.
                // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort() in .NET 8.
                // You must design GetNextItemAsync/ProcessItemAsync to
                // respect the CancellationToken.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

**1. You cannot force-kill work in .NET 8.**
`Thread.Abort()` is gone with no replacement. Every blocking call (`GetNextItem`) must accept a `CancellationToken` or you'll hang on shutdown. If you're wrapping a legacy sync API that can't be cancelled:

```csharp
// Escape hatch — run on a thread you can abandon (leaks the thread)
var item = await Task.Run(() => GetNextItemSync(), ct)
                     .WaitAsync(ct); // detaches on cancel, thread keeps running
```

**2. `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks become dead code.**
Replace with `OperationCanceledException`. Use `when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish cancellation from bugs.

**3. `volatile bool` isn't enough for async code.**
`CancellationToken` integrates with `async/await`, `WaitHandle`, `Channel<T>`, and most BCL APIs. A `volatile bool` can't unblock a call that's waiting on I/O or a semaphore.

**4. If this runs in ASP.NET Core or a Generic Host, use `BackgroundService`:**

```csharp
public class ProcessorService : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        // stoppingToken fires on host shutdown — no manual wiring needed
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration: builder.Services.AddHostedService<ProcessorService>();
```

**5. `Thread.Sleep` → `await Task.Delay`.**
`Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread pool thread. Use `await Task.Delay(timeout, ct)` which is both cancellable and non-blocking.
